Residuals diagnostics

In general, for time series models we are going to check 4 properties of the residuals:

  1. Autocorrelation of the residuals (information left on the residuals).
  2. Zero mean of the residuals (bias of the forecasts).
  3. Constant variance of the residuals (homoscedasticity).
  4. Normal distribution of the residuals.

1 and 2 are definitely more relevant when assessing the model. A model that does not satisfy them can be improved upon. Several methods may satisfy them and we may need to select among them.

  • Bias is easy to fix by subtracting the mean of your residuals from your forecasts.

  • Autocorrelation is less difficult to fix. You may need to include auto regressive terms, external aggressors or change the model altogether. We will deal with these topics later in the subject.

3 and 4 are useful to easily compute prediction intervals and to have prediction intervals that are not too wide.

  • Apart from a box-cox transformation, there is usually little you can do to ensure the normality and heteroscedasticity of your residuals.

  • There are alternative approaches to computing the prediction intervals (bootstrapping) that will allow us to produce confidence intervals even in these situations.

Please read carefully section 5.4 of the book as well as the pdf uploaded to blackboard.

The properties above are general checkpoints for time series models. Some specific models (e.g linear models) will require that we do some additional checks on the residuals. We will see this in due course.

model_vals <- bricks_fit %>% augment()
model_vals %>% 
  filter(.model == "Mean") %>%
  autoplot(Bricks, colour = "gray") +
  geom_line(aes(y=.fitted), colour = "blue", linetype = "dashed")

bricks_fit %>% 
  select(Mean) %>% # Selects the Mean model
  gg_tsresiduals()

# Compute the mean of the residuals
model_vals %>% as_tibble() %>%
  filter(.model == "Mean") %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(.innov, na.rm = TRUE))

# Generate qq_plot

# Generate box-plot
p2 <- ggplot(data = mean_vals, aes(y = .innov)) +
      geom_boxplot(fill="light blue", alpha = 0.7) +
      stat_summary(aes(x=0), fun="mean", colour= "red") # Include the mean

p1 + p2
Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_segment).

  1. The residuals are highly correlated, as the correlogram clearly shows (ACF values outside the dashed bounds)
  • In this case this is clearly related to the simplicity of the model. The residuals look exactly like the time plot, only shifted by the mean of the time series.
  • We are barely using information in the model. To fix this we would need to change the model.
  1. The residuals have mean 0 (they are the series shifted by the mean of the series)
  2. Visual inspection of the variance of the residuals across historical data indicates lack of homoscedasticity. There are recession periods (such as 1982 or 1974) where the variation of the series is much higher.
  • NOTE: visual inspection is not a substitute for formal testing, but we will spare that for now.
  1. Visual inspection agrees with the hypothesis that the residuals are fairly normal. The histogram seems relatively bell shaped and the distribution adjusts fairly well to the QQ-plot (except on the tails and perhaps a bit in the middle). The boxplot further confirms the relative symmetry of the distribution, showing as well that the mean is close to the median.
  • To formally assess the normality we would need to perform a test, something we will not do for now.
  • Understand that the normality check is applied to the unordered set of residuals (the frequency distribution of the residuals). We may have residuals that follow a normal distribution but that are arranged in a heteroscedastic manner.

    1. The histogram, qq-plot and box-plot clearly show how the residuals are not normal.

Portmanteau tests for autocorrelation

Checking if each autocorrelation coefficient is within the negligible autocorrelation limits is equivalent to carrying out multiple hypothesis tests, each one with a small probability of giving a false positive. When performing multiple tests, it is likely that at least one will give a false positive.

A possible solution is to test whether the first \(l\) autocorreltaion coefficients differ much from the expected outcome for a white noise process. Carrying a test on multiple ACFs is sometimes called a portmanteau test, from the french word describing a rack carrying several items of clothing.

There are different possible statistics for Portmanteau tests:

Box-Pierce Statistic:

\[\begin{align*} Q = T \sum_{k=1}^\ell r_k^2, \end{align*}\]
  • \(l\) is the maximum lag being considered
  • \(T\) is the number of observations
  • \(r_k\) is the k-th autocorrelation coefficient

Ljung-Box Statistic

\[\begin{align*} Q^* = T(T+2) \sum_{k=1}^\ell (T-k)^{-1}r_k^2. \end{align*}\]
  • \(l\) is the maximum lag being considered
  • \(T\) is the number of observations
  • \(r_k\) is the k-th autocorrelation coefficient

Main idea behind both tests:

Instead of evaluating the magnitude of each autocorrelation coefficient, we seek to generate a metric of the overall ammount of autocorrelation of the series. Both the Box-Pierce and Ljung-Box statistic grow as the amount of autocorrelation in the series grows. This is because the terms within the sum are proportional to \(r_k^2\), achieving two things:

  1. All the terms of the sum are greater than 0. The greater the autocorrelation of the different lags, the greater the statistic.
  2. Very small autocorrelations become much smaller when squaring them, while medium-large autocorrelations remain relevant in the sum when squaring them. In fact, all autocorrelations become smaller when squaring them because they are \(\leq 1\). But the smaller the autocorrelation, the more its initial module is reduced when squaring it. This ensures that very small auto-correlation coefficients do not substantially contribute to the growth of the statistic while medium-large autcorrelation coefficients remain relevant within the sum of the statistic.

The examples below might seem obvious but are worth giving some thought (this idea of squaring is prevalent in the logic behind many statistics and formulas):

  • \(0.9 * 0.9 = 0.81\) : reduction of 10% of the initial module (\(1 - 0.9 = 0.1\))
  • \(0.7 * 0.7 = 0.49\) : redoction of 30% of the initial module (\(1 - 0.7 = 0.3\))
  • \(0.5 * 0.5 = 0.25\) : reduction of 50% of the initial module (\(1 - 0.5 = 0.5\))
  • \(0.25 * 0.25 = 0.0625\) : reduction of 75% of the initial module (\(1-0.25 = 0.25\))
  • \(0.1 * 0.1 = 0.01\) : reduction of 90% of the initial module (\(1 - 0.1 = 0.9\))

So, summarizing:

  • If each \(r_k\) is close to 0 (small autocorrelation), then \(Q\) (or \(Q*\)) will be small.
  • If some \(r_k\) values are large (positive or negative), then \(Q\) (or \(Q*\)) will be large.

Suggested values for \(l\):

\(l\) (the number of terms in the sum) is something we need to choose. The following recommendations are to be followed

  • \(l = 10\) for non-seasonal data

  • \(l = 2m\) for seasonal data, where \(m\) is the period of seasonality

  • Caution:

    • The test is not good if \(T/l < 5\). If the suggested values are greater than this threshold, use \(l = T/5\).

Distribution of the statistic:

  • \(H_0: r_{ks}\;come\;from\;white\;noise\).
    • In this case \(Q\) and \(Q*\) would follow a \(\chi^2\) distribution with \((l-K)\) degrees of freedom, where \(K\) is the number of parameters in the model.
      • If we are calculating the autocorrelation coefficients from raw data and not the autocorrelation of the residuals of a certain model, set \(K=0\) for the test.
  • \(H_1: r_{ks}\;do\;not\;come\;from\;white\;noise\)

Interpretation of the test:

The test is a right-tailed test. Under \(H_0\) (residuals are non-correlated), the value of the statistic should be small and we should remain in the âfail to rejectâ region. If the statistic resulting from our series is too high, we enter the rejection region. Those values of the statistic have very low probability of occurrence if \(H_0\) is true. Thus, we would reject if the the statistic is big enough (p-value is sufficiently small).

As usual, we set a confidence level \(\alpha\) to maintain type I error under control. We then compute the statistic and its associated p-value. If its p-value is smaller than alpha, we reject \(H_0\). Otherwise we fail to reject \(H_0\).

How to determine K, number of parameters of the model

This can be done with the function tidy() applied to the fitted model. However, in this particular case, because decomposition_model() uses a combination of models, it is necessary to assess the number of parameters of each individual model and then sum them. If we apply tidy() to the model fitted using decomposition_model() we get the following error pointing us to this fact:

tidy(fit_dcmp)
Error in `mutate_cols()`:
! Problem with `mutate()` input `..1`.
i `..1 = dplyr::across(all_of(mbl_vars), function(x) lapply(x, tidy, ...))`.
x no applicable method for 'tidy' applied to an object of class "c('decomposition_model', 'model_combination')"
Caused by error in `UseMethod()`:
! no applicable method for 'tidy' applied to an object of class "c('decomposition_model', 'model_combination')"

So we now proceed to see how many parameters each of the individual models has:

Number of parameters of the drift model:

dcmp <- retail_series %>%
        model(stl = STL(log(Turnover))) %>%
        components()

season_adjust <- dcmp %>% select(season_adjust)

fit_drift <- season_adjust %>%
             model(Drift = RW(season_adjust ~ drift()))

tidy(fit_drift)
# A tibble: 1 x 6
  .model term  estimate std.error statistic p.value
  <chr>  <chr>    <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
1 Drift  b      0.00441   0.00318      1.39   0.166
# We see that only one parameter is involved in fitting the drift model.

Number of parameters of the seasonal naive model

seasonal <- select(dcmp, season_year)

fit_snaive <- seasonal %>% model(SNaive = SNAIVE(season_year ~ lag("year")))

tidy(fit_snaive)
# A tibble: 0 x 6

#   std.error <dbl>, statistic <dbl>, p.value <dbl>
# We see that no parameters are involved in fitting the seasonal naive model (as expected)

Number of parameters of decomposition_model():

In this case we are choosing to:

  • Predict the seasonally adjusted component using a drift model (1 parameter)
  • Predict the seasonal component using a seasonal naive model (0 parameters)

So the total number of parameters of decomposition_model() is 1 + 0 = 1.

We will therefore set \(K=1\) in the formula for the degrees of freedom of the Box-Pierce and Ljung-Box tests: \(l-K\). Remember that it is necessary to know the degrees of freedom

Obtaining the Box-Pierce and Ljung-Box statistics:

we will use the functions augment() to obtain the residuals and then features() from the fabletools library applied to the innovation residuals.

In the following code lag = \(l\) and dof = \(K\).

IMPORTANT WARNING: the Box-Pierce and Ljung-Box statistics will follow a \(\chi^2\) distribution with \(l-K\) degrees of freedom if \(H_0\) is true, but in the code below dof refers to the numbers of degrees of freedom constrained by the model (that is, the number \(K\) of parameters in the model). The way it is coding is confusing, so please beware of this difference when coding.

fit_dcmp %>% augment() %>% features(.innov, box_pierce, lag = 24, dof = 1)
# A tibble: 1 x 5
  State              Industry                            .model bp_stat bp_pva~1
  <chr>              <chr>                               <chr>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 Northern Territory Clothing, footwear and personal ac~ decomp    109. 3.12e-13
# ... with abbreviated variable name 1: bp_pvalue
fit_dcmp %>% augment() %>% features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 24, dof = 1)
# A tibble: 1 x 5
  State              Industry                            .model lb_stat lb_pva~1
  <chr>              <chr>                               <chr>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 Northern Territory Clothing, footwear and personal ac~ decomp    113. 7.44e-14
# ... with abbreviated variable name 1: lb_pvalue

In both cases the p-value is much smaller than 0.05 and even than 0.01, so we can reject \(H_0\) with a 99% confidence level. In other words, the residuals do not come from a white noise series and are therefore correlated.
